And the taming collars are shock collars that shock the predators when they get a little too emotional. So as in when they excited, angry and among other emotional emotions they will get shocked. text:
Lemme say something. When you actually use this as an allegory for racism thinking about black and white, the slight nonsensical nature is obvious. Like you said it's not like black people had magic powers or anything, sure.
But when you think about the reasons for asian people to view western society as 'untrustworthy' is because of their actual history. They were the oppressing party not so long ago. So the internal discrimination is there. 
This is the same among people who belong to different religions/cultures - due to actual historical events people are prejudiced. 
If you call out a german citizen or a japanese citizen for their action in world war 2, would it be fair ? But then that is based on history, isn't it? True history.
Here also predators used to hunt down prey. Yes. But it says that it was thousands of years ago. THOUSANDS
This is not the same predators and preys we see in our animal world. This is a different world. So predators were not a threat for thousands of years. The fear is based on plain history. 
So when viewed like that, this can be considered as a good allegory for racism. Just not in the way we think on surface level.

I actually really like your point about the whole racism/ homophobia/ discrimination metaphors. In these movies, there is usually some kind of justification of why these people don't liek them. It's because like you said they are eating brains, or have some other very clearly dangerous aspect to them. It just doesnt work, because that's not what racism/ any other kind of discrimination is. it's based on nothing but prejudice and hatred. 

I feel like one of the only metaphors that I've ever seen work for this is Wicked. That's it. the whole point of racism is that it's unjustifiable, and by comparing it to relatively justifiable things (like not wanting to be eaten by a zombie) it kinda of... I dont know. it's just weird and not getting the point across that I think they are intending.

text:
16:35 I‚Äôm a little late, but as a nb trans white woman, I totally got what you were trying to say and agree with you 100%, even if you didn‚Äôt express it in the clearest way. And obvi i‚Äôm white so I‚Äôm not trying to speak over black woman, just trying to add perspective as a different minority. Also, as both a minority and an ally, I‚Äôd definitely suggest you don‚Äôt overthink things. Cis/straight/white people can have great takes that their minority counterparts either haven‚Äôt fully articulated yet because to them it‚Äôs just an obvious fact of life, or have articulated and nobody listened, and unfortunately, sometimes it just takes a white/cis/straight/male person to get other people to listen. That said, a lot of this kind of media analysis has probably been done by that minority group already, and they‚Äôre probably a lot smaller than you, so if you can find it, it‚Äôs always great imo to uplift small minority channels and writers. So don‚Äôt overthink things, because as long as you give it a good, honest effort (especially if you read books! If you read just like 1 or 2 books in a subject you‚Äôll already be more of an ally than 90% of people are), you give a genuine effort to be in community and establish real relationships with minorities, and you treat us like people fully and not dehumanize us, I promise you are doing much better than you think. And also, most minorities you‚Äôll meet wont know the intimacies of theory, only their actual lived experiences, so just listen, and don‚Äôt quote literature at them like you know more than them from reading a single book, even when you are ‚Äúright‚Äù. Just listen and be a good person and be chill and I promise you you‚Äôre a great ally. It‚Äôs ok to do the best you can, because that‚Äôs all that you can do. And if you‚Äôre reading this and think you can do better, I challenge you to do better. Pick up a book, find community with different people, have meaningful conversations. But just relax, because I promise you‚Äôre doing better than you think you are. 

Sending love ‚ù§‚ù§

text:
Also I want to add to that last bit two caveats, which sound hypocritical on the surface but they aren‚Äôt so hang out with the dialectic for me:

If you genuinely cannot engage more deeply with this stuff because of how busy you are or health reasons or mental health reasons or neurodivergent reasons or economic reasons, that is all valid, but also, don‚Äôt try to use perceived businesses to ignore this stuff because you don‚Äôt feel like it and put it off. Like if you spend 3 hours gaming to decompress from work, valid, but just spend 15 minutes doing this stuff. Read a chapter of a book, text that queer friend you haven‚Äôt talked to in a while and just have a conversation, or heck even have a video essay on in the background, whatever will get you more engaged in being a better ally. It doesn‚Äôt need to be complex or hard but it does need to happen.


Also, for my adhd friends, the ‚ÄúI could be better‚Äù and the ‚ÄúI have to give myself grace because of my adhd‚Äù thoughts can and should co-exist. Just remember that your condition is valid and it makes sense why you have trouble and beating yourself up about it doesn‚Äôt help, and you‚Äôll never be able to reach your ‚Äúfull potential‚Äù because it‚Äôs humanly impossible for neurotypical people, let alone neurodivergent ones. You cannot be in a state of hyperfocus 24/7 to min max your day, you have to take breaks. But also, there are medications you can take and strategies you can use to help you, but you have to work with your friends and family and team of medical professionals and most importantly, yourself. As long as you‚Äôre trying to improve things and be more focused and you give things a genuine shot, you are doing your best and things will improve, even if it‚Äôs slowly or non-linearly.

Sorry I just went on a tangent there, my adhd meds ran out a week ago bc I lost my insurance and I‚Äôm giving myself a pep talk to feel better.

text: Zootopia accidentally stumbled into an argument against historically oppressed groups, using their generational trauma as a reason for repressing their former oppressor group. The positions of power in Zootopia are disproportionately held by predators who historically preyed upon the prey animals; this makes the predators allegories for white people, whether or not that was the intention of the writers. This interpretation of the movie fits the symbolic choices they made somewhat better than the reverse.

text:
I find the allegory makes more sense if you see predators not as an allegory for Western minorities, but global minorities.
Because yeah. European people did some messed up stuff. A lot didn't. Mostly it was just continuing what they knew worked.
With technological advances, they were also more dangerous to face than for example people in Central Africa or India, to continue with the pattern of British people.

But that doesn't mean today they see "minorities" as prey. But as equal members of society. Using the analogy of Police in this context as well, with Judy joining a predominantly Predator and Large Animal policeforce as a rodent, it further solidifies minorities being the small prey animals in this allegory.
The message is to not demonize people for their genetic makeup. And not to judge them for the wrongdoings of their ancestors.

text:
You know, I'm not sure I ever really thought about this until just now, but I think something that gets left out of most discussions around the allegorical nature of "predators" and "prey" animals in Zootopia is that the movie seems to pretty heavily imply that the story being told at the start of the movie (where Judy plays a bunny being brutally murdered lol) is not an actual historical account of things. It seems more like a revisionist "history" or racist (speciesist?) mythology being spread by a bunch of backwoods hicks who need a story to justify their bigotry against particular groups. 

This explains why Nick was so bewildered when Judy started talking about "predator DNA" like it was a factual thing. Even after all they'd been through, there was still that bit of racist  propaganda that she'd retained from her childhood. Which parallels a lot of the sentiment we see from "liberal" moderates, who are happy to express their lack of bigotry towards various minority groups, but will still openly support certain policies that are based in bigotry, because they haven't actually done the work to unpack the ways they were indoctrinated by racist systems since they were too young to recognize them as such. 

I do agree that the metaphor can get a little muddy at times, but I don't think this one is quite as bad a case as stuff like X-men or other stories about superpowered humans being persecuted for the very real danger they present to humans without those powers. Is there any "predator" animal in Zootopia that's taking on an elephant? Is a fennec fox any danger to a bison or a giraffe? Is a mouse a predator or prey? It's not really clear why the distinction would exist in this world when there's such a huge range of sizes in animals unless it's nothing more than a fable that still gets spread around in more rural areas where the population is primarily made up of "prey" animals.

text: 10:34 "Reckless endangerment" is actually a thing that is taken relatively serious in Europe. We'd never have the police chases that happen in the US, because once it gets too dangerous, the police lets off. That's how a lot of ATM bombers and smugglers get away in Germany, they drive to the countryside border to the Netherlands where they can drive fast relatively safely, but most of the time the police will deem these chases too dangerous and quit. And no, crossing the border is not enough to escape, we have deals with other countries that allow police to cross borders until the given country's police can take over.

text:
The crazy thing is how much the idea for this movie changed. They even have some early scenes like 80% done that you can find. The original idea was that they were actually afraid that Predators would attack if they got two excited and kept shock collars on them (weirdly topical) that would shock them anytime they got too excited. I've seen two scenes from this early concept.

One has a polar bear kid having his quinceanera type party to get his collar. As he gets it and "becomes an adult" he gets excited and starts dancing. Only to be shocked as he does. And the scene ends with him turning to look at his parents suddenly realizing what this really means.

The other scene has Nick (apparently, he was the main character originally) at a doctor's office as they remove his collar from him for a procedure. And he is noticeably miserable with the collar on. However, as soon as they take it off a cage drops around him. He starts to rub his neck, and it slowly dawns on him that he is free of the collar. He starts looking real happy but just before he does anything, they snap the collar back on.

Considering how far along both scenes were this was clearly the plan up for a while. Probably both created as proof of concept. Not sure when or why this changed. Perhaps they couldn't write a good enough story around it or felt it was a little too black and white and preferred a more nuanced story. No idea. But it's always in the back of my mind when this movie does come up.

... Allegories for racism certainly can be badly done, but talking about certain types of people being genetically predisposed to being violent is literally just a thing many people did and still do think about other humans, and these beliefs absolutely have been entangled with opinions on development. There's even the term paternalism for the attitude that it is the role of the genetically superior and enlightened to educate and guide their "primitive inferiors."

And the fact you're drawing in an entirely different series to use as your comparison here shows that even you recognize that your criticism isn't really applicable to zootopia.

Even were there to be a clear distinction between the power of predator/non-predator animals, which there isn't in zootopia's world, but whatever, that still wouldn't make it a bad analogue, because even if that's not true of humans, we've absolutely believed that it was.

text:
My kids have been watching this in the car constantly for the last few months. So, I can quote it better than I can quote Search for the Holy Grail, I still haven't actually seen it all the way through. Over time, I've developed a few ideas:

I think this is a remake of 48 hours with Nick in Eddie Murphy's roll. (Remake the way A fist Full od Dollars is a remake of Yojimbo.) In any case, it's a really good reason for me to rewatch 48 Hours to verify my suspicion.

You could write a book on leadership from Chief Bogo's scenes. He's not as bad a leader as I think the movie wants you to think. Yeah, he does make some bad calls. But a lot of the stuff he does that seems dismissive is trying to keep an aggressive, naive, high Int low Wis character under control until she learns how the real world works. I mean, she's averaging a threat of making a felony arrest a day to force people to do what she wants, that's not really the kind of judgment call I'd trust someone with 1-2 days on the job to make. What would happen if he actually encouraged her to "make the world a better place?"

Assistant Mayor Bellweather isn't a bad villain. We first encounter her basking in the limelight of being on stage with the mayor. Then I think they're leaning on the trope that the assistant is the real force behind the executive getting anything done. She needs the missing animals to be found, and knows there is an aggressive, naive, high Int low Wis cop just looking to make a name for herself, so I think it's reasonable to assume that it's no accident she showed up at just the right time to get Judy onto the case. She even played the role of good guy until Judy figured it out, so when she did monologue, she wasn't really revealing any new information.

Also, the first time I heard the press conference, I actually told my wife "She was set up to fail by not being prepped." It took me a couple more listenings to realize that the movie wasn't using the press conference to build the relationship with Nick, but that she actually was set up to fail and rile up the city. That advanced Bellweather's plan.

I 100% agree on the problems with metaphors about racism. But I did notice two things they did well: When Judy first meets Nick, she compliments him for doing something that pretty much should be normal, and can't think of a real compliment, so she ends up with the awkward "real articulate guy." Then, after the press conference, she can't even see how what she said could harm Nick. She couldn't see outside her own circumstances. I think they did a good job of making the point that meaning well doesn't always translate to doing well, especially when you're an outsider.

You may or may not like the movie, but I agree: They did a solid job at story telling. They didn't try to get fancy by subverting the process, they told a story, and it made sense.

Edit: Also, the joke "I no longer have to be a lonely hunter, now I can hunt for tax deductions. I want to be an actuary!" Will never not make my day.

text:
Totally with you on the allegory. It's really a stupid thing to claim that someone with very dangerous abilities is comparable to someone from a vulnerable group. However, there is one reading I can see kinda working, although it's a bit muddied by other allegories going on in the film. We could see the prey-predator dynamic as reflecting female-male dynamics. There is a difference in biology there, and historically males have preyed on females and often have a major advantage over them. Males have traditionally held power, and in a newly more equal society there are still many ways in which traditional male characteristics are prized over female ones, but as females come to dominate some industries, that's being turned on its head. Of course I'm still not a fan of equating one whole group of people to predators/carnivores,  but it does work much better than comparing predators to Black people or White people or Gay people. The film does allude to how people preferred Lionheart with his tradional masculine characteristics over Bellwether, who was more traditionally feminine and treated as lesser by Lionheart because of it. 

X-Men is just a lost cause. Too stupid and racist/sexist/homophobic no matter how they slice it. At best, the allegory works if it's about talent, which transcends all those things, can grant great power and sometimes animosity.

text:
The reasons for prey fearing predators is definitely more rooted in truth, and therefore harder to correlate with our own society - I fully agree with that. BUT, I do want to highlight that there are likely people out there who legitimately fear those who are "different". They are often raised to fear certain types of people and spend their lives subconsciously looking for news stories and lived experiences that reinforce that fear. Especially if it's a fear shared by their loved ones or community

Most of us, myself, included, will agree that those fears aren't based off of reality and are formed entirely off of prejudice. However, to them it feels very real. I think the predators vs prey allegory in this movie kind of speaks to those people and allows us a window into their reality. I mean, prey have been historically killed by predators for years. Why should we believe that they couldn't do it again, when there's so much to risk? Obviously it's not quite as extreme in our society, but whatever these people are raised to believe about people who are "different', it very much becomes their reality. 

It seems like they're saying "yes, in your bubble with your upbringing, I can see why you'd be afraid. But it really doesn't have to be this way, and you don't have to live in fear forever". 

Acknowledging where people are coming from, even if we don't agree, can put us in a better position to help them without judgement

text: Of all the movies, Zootopia is the one movie which actually does the racism metaphor really well, and this is coming from a guy who's normally not interested in this stuff. Weird choice to point out the X-Men issue here. Mutants can accidentally kill people or destroy cities, so yeah, the prejudice isn't entirely unjustified. In Zootopia the prejudice comes from behaviors they supposedly grew out of -- in other words, stereotypes. A good amount of Racial Hate comes from fear and disgust of the stereotypes people have of them. Like the movie even tells us that, herbivores can go feral too, so there's nothing inherently different, its just a matter of how they used to live that influenced their behaviors. Now that the conditions are the same (or similar), that divide really is gone... except in the minds.

text:
Also, yes the allegory is lost when you make it too extreme. The entire point about rights for all humans is that they are in fact human and just like everyone else. They are not more or less of a danger due to whatever superficial differences they have.
IE: take a blonde and a brunette. Different hair colors, neither are genetically predisposed to anything  that constitutes being more or less dangerous due to those factors. That is what racism is. Assumption that a person based purely on race is better, worse than another or has an attribute not at all proven (IE: you have a slightly higher chance of going blind if you have less melanin in your eyes purely due to the science. It's also not significantly greater than eyes just getting worse with age.)  by science/medicine and even in cases where it is (IE: genetic propensity for instance) it's not treated as a pariah. It is simply a thing you are aware of and get help for when and if needed and nothing more. Just like many things are treated today. (though more need to be given this treatment and help should be given when needed and it's often not.)

Also, making the allegory minority unequivocally better than the other makes the entire thing more skewed too. IE if black people were werewolves and that came with many benefits, being black would be better. Imagine if Harry Potter was real. Being a wizard is better than a muggle. You lose the entire point when you make the objectively cooler, more capable, better evolution adapted by a large margin group the pushed down minority. Being predator vs prey in zootopia has no real advantage. More than anything, it's just size or body capability IE elephants have super dexterous trunks, hand/paws might be more useful than hooves. That kind of thing and clearly in zootopia, they evolved to do many things around that or use their appendages like hands regardless. There is no advantage or disadvantage to being prey or predator. 

And yes, I always thought the genuine history of evolutional struggle was a decent enough conclusion, but it caused issues because society isn't scientific regarding that. Also, the same would apply to prey animals who were once extremely aggressive and territorial.

text: For me the predator-minority thing holds up to be a purposely flawed metaphor, because it reminds me of Lombroso‚Äôs criminal theory- that some people with certain biological characteristics are predisposed to crime, as these characteristics are indicators that this person is less evolved than someone without them. He argued that stuff like long arms, long jaws, thick eyebrows and larger irregular faces showed someone was less evolved and therefore a born criminal (obviously pro-white European racist bullshit). So if you swap out long jaws and long arms for the typical characteristics of an animal predator- sharp teeth and larger bodies, it‚Äôs kinda the same. Characteristics that turn a group into the ‚Äòother‚Äô to conveniently reflect dominant racial supremacy attitudes at the time. Yeah in the film the prey was hunted by the predator thousands of years ago, but none of the remaining animals have direct experience of that in their lifetime, they fear predators again because of the hysteria created by old biological prejudice from generations ago. To me it shows how although scientific racism is universally seen as wrong and outdated, it‚Äôs still damaging when the system needs to use it as a scapegoat, or the media decides to sell it as a story. I bet Disney wasn‚Äôt thinking about it that way, but its valuable to me that I can watch a film at age 11 because I thought the fox was fit, and then watch it again at age 20 and see how much it can relate to my childhood experiences being mixed race in Northern England, and with all the right wing chatter happening today. Still think the fox is fit though sorry.

text:
I agree with your point about the allegory for black people/gay people/other minorities etc. But I think the general purpose of these kind of allegories is that fear should not equal hate. Racism and homophobia are about how people FEEL about that group, not about the group itself. It's about how the prey FEELS about the predators. And yes obviously we see it and are like "duh I'd be scared too if I was a little rabbit and there were a bunch of huge lions around". But that isn't the point. The point is that no matter how scared you are of something. No matter how strange and different it seems and how little you understand it. No matter what general history and personal history there is, they deserve to be treated like a person(or animal in this case lol). You SHOULD NOT devalue them or alienate them, no matter your initial response, because we are a part of the same humanity. And I think X-men and Zootopia capture that. 
It's not about how similar the predators are to black people. Or how similar the x-men are to gay people. It's not about them. It's about the people hating and fearing them.

text:
The whole "racism" allegory was done even worse in Elemental. In that movie, Fire People were the "Bad Race", the one you should avoid. While in Zootopia they were clearly going for black=predator, here it's Fire= Korean/Filipino. 
But the issue here is, unlike the predators which are, at present, completely harmless unless they choose to be aggressive, the Fire People are objectively, inarguably more dangerous than ANY of the other elements. They are naturally hazardous to Plant people, can kill themself AND someone else if they get too close to Water, and are simply uncomfortable for Air. These are all facts that have nothing to do with the personality of the Fire Person in question. It would be like if all Asian people had a disease that was completely harmless to other Asians, but was fatal if given to a person of ANY other race, meaning Asians would literally have to be ostracized from the rest of the world. 
But yeah... that's obviously not how it works. Asians are just people, not naturally dangerous beings that become a threat to everyone and everything around them.

text:
The brilliance of the prejudice narrative in Zootopia is there IS no straightforward parallel to real life, so the viewer can't take the "right side" and not examine their own prejudices.
EDIT: The way I read the film, the predators are not a parallel to black people or any marginalized group. There is elements of that, but the power predators have is so engrained into the story that that reading doesn't work. The predators are more of a minority, yes, but they hold most of the power, too. The prey animals are more victimized and pigeon-holed into certain roles (eg farmers), but they are the majority. I don't know if they did this on purpose, but it works for the story if not for allegory.

text:
It helps me to think it's not that the divides are being created to be an allegory for racism but simply if you're going to have a world of this kind of world building one of the first things you have to figure out is how different type of actions are going to interact with one another 

Like if humans can't even tolerate each other for looking different in what society is there going to be a group of people who actually do have different abilities that are not going to be treated differently? 

Humans get squirmy if somebody has an unrealistically good memory, you think they aren't going to freak out if somebody actually has super powers? 

It's not a specific racial allegory but a simple factor of world-building that will almost always be applicable to any category in the real world because that's just how nature is 

There are other animals that have been confirmed to have racism in them like dolphins will harass other types of dolphins for looking different than them.

text:
I actually think the predator fear works symbolically. The predators ate the prey animals thousands of years ago and a lot of prey animals still resent the predators for it. I think this can be compared to things like early american slave trade, korean subjugation by japan, and other historical events where one group commits atrocities against another, leading to resentment hundreds of years later. 

Its also interesting that the predators are portrayed as the established power. The mayor is a predator and Judy gets into the police force via an inclusivity program. I think that adds credence to this reading. What do y‚Äôall think?

text:
As trans guy and a huge X-Men fan I have to agree with your take on metaphors as a stand in for minorities, however I feel like I have to make a case for X-Men. Because it does not work as an excuse for not having actual minorities (i.e gay or black acharacter) in your medium. However, despite the mutant metaphor being  of course not always applicaple (we all know nobody is suddenly going to develope superpowers) for one minority group it can be utilised in a way to show the effects of discrimination. And I do believe that is something X-Men does very well, because they are carful to include actual minorities in their group to mirror actual oppression. I.e Bobby/Iceman who is gay and has a monologue about being gay and a mutant when coming out, or Ororo/Storm as a black women, or Kitty/Shadowcat as a jewish woman (you get what I mean) the point it does not use the mutant metaphor as an exchangable thing from other discrimination but and extension and I think that does seperate them from other mediums I know because they are usually lacking actual representation them. And it's not like this is new thing for X-Men, I mean look at New Mutants from the 80s, of course the representation is far from flawless but they tried something way more diverse to show actual minorities. Another exapmle is of course Magneto, who is a survior of Ausschwitz. And for me, someone with a non-visible disability, seeing somebody like Scott/Cyclops face discrimination due to his disability (very much linked to his powers) and still fighting for his rights and those of others is just really inspiring.
Oh, also the mutants being gay thing is probably thanks to Chris Claremont who very much queercoded the X-Men in the 70s, so it isn't that far fetched xD. Anyway, great video just wanted to eleborate on that. Also, super random but every time I think of Zootopia I have to think about the many names it has. Because here in Germany it's Zoomania (no idea why) and in Canada it's (according to Disney+ there) Zootropolis and I think that's hilarious because none of the other titles makes that much sense. 
Have a good one.

The comparison I made was that it‚Äôd be like vampires integrating into our society, beings who still have biological needs (blood vs protein). Vampires are still very much apex killing machines. text:
Funny thing about this movie, even though it's framed as them looking down on Judy and not taking her seriously, it's actually quite common for most jobs to start new hires on more "trivial" stuff before letting them do more "serious" stuff. She did parking tickets for like two days then started acting like she had been dying inside for ten years. Yes them not putting her into the system on day one was messed up, and a definite sign that they didn't consider her to be a legitimate part of the force, but there's a lot that the entertainment industry gets wrong when it comes to the police and how they do things. ( It's a symptom of the desire to make things more engaging, for the sake of making a bigger profit, or for the love of entertaining others ).

Edit: I also noticed another plot hole, since the "feral" mental devolution of the victims was drug induced it should have worn off on its own after a while, so that means that someone was sneaking more doses of the night howlers into their systems.

text:
I love the way there's the obvious divide between predators and prey, but there's also the subtler divide between the big and small animals in each. Stuff like the sheep assistant mayor having to work for the lion mayor, and siding with Judy because "us little guys really need to stick together" (as they both try to help a small predator, the otter looking for her husband), and the fact there are prey police officers, just not small police officers, meaning that her not being "good enough" isn't based on her being a prey animal, even though that's the main divide framed by the film, but based on her being small, like Nick (a small predator), and they come together and prove they're just as good. Hell, the police chief is a large prey animal, and we see several others as police, showing that prey can be just as tough and ruthless as predators, and Mr Big is a small prey animal that commands an army of HUGE predators.
Also, pretty sure Mr Big and family are Shrews or Voles, not Possums.

text:
SIZE Discrimination is the most significant issue for many in the city of Zootopia. 
The Mammal Inclusion Initiative wasn't about bunnies, or prey, or females; it was about allowing smaller mammals into roles that they had been excluded from. The ZPD had been restricted to mammals of wolf-size or larger; so they weren't very responsive to the needs of smaller folk. 
Mr. Big is the 'law' in Little Rodentia (he built it!) and smaller mammals (like Otterton) come to him with their concerns; not the ZPD. The MII is an attempt to change this.

Yes, there was that connection between the victims, but there's still a lot of unknowns at that time. However, Judy in her inexperience, was easily lead by those question and then started to make statements that had no hard evidence supporting it. 

A more seasoned officer would've said something along the lines of, "We are still gathering information on 'going savage,' but rest assure, we will not stop until this phenomenon is solved and all of the victims are returned safely to their families."

text:
¬†@Edriely¬† Yeah, a real press conference might have the hero cop make a prepared statement, but a professional handle the follow up questions. And one of the hardest things to say is "I don't know."

The movie does an excellent job of set up and pay off here. They set up the "savage predators" idea from the very beginning. Then they put the words "could be part of their biology" out there in a context where that speculation is not only reasonable but important. (I.e. "We need to investigate potential sources of this medical condition.") So, none of this comes out of nowhere, it's almost inevitable that the inexperienced person is going to try and come up with an answer when they're in the stressful/exciting situation, they latch on to something they heard earlier, and they conjecture instead of answering "I don't know." She didn't even realize that she was conjecturing.

text: 21:00 I absolutely agree. Modern Disney has totally abandoned actual storytelling (which requires a problem/want, an action taken in response to that problem/want, and consequences that follow based on those). I'm an animator so my best guess is that suits come into a project and they want to change one scene, then later they want to change another scene, etc. but by the end of the movie it's like they've poked so many holes in the foundation that the house doesn't stand anymore and the plot no longer makes sense or has any motivation/clear line to follow. It's really depressing. There's a definite lack of consideration for the "but why?" in modern Disney. For example in Wish Magnifico doesn't grant everyone's wishes. But why? Does it drain his power? Does it make them more pliable and easier to control as a population? Does holding their wishes give him power to reshape the wishes? Asha is mad that Magnifico doesn't grant all the wishes. But why? Aren't there people with dangerous or conflicting wishes? Would it be a good thing to grant them all? Modern Disney is riddled with stuff like this where it seems like they want a certain archetype or vignette, but they don't bother to think through (or at least show) the ramifications, lead-up, justifications, or results of that thing. It kind of reminds me of first-time DnD players who don't know how their character would react to things (because they haven't thought through the how/why their character got to the present).

text:
predators never struck me as black people. they struck to me as white people who used to be racist as a whole a long time ago, but not through their individual wrongdoing (its just how most were brought up back in the day). and have since changed and reformed but still have the fear of prejudice being engrained in the minds of the minorities, some of whom take it out on them unfairly as a result.

This explains several features of the world that the straight up black vs white angle cannot
1. predators are in positions of power and even the lion mayor chooses a sheep assistant mayor to "Get the sheep vote". To all followers of the 2020 US presidential election, this should sound really familiar
2. Predators "biological instinct" to be primitive and savage makes much more sense when you consider the analogy is now to white people's past impulsion to conquer and enslave other peoples, simply due to different outdated principles in the past
3. Gideon Gray is mean to Judy in her youth but is now reformed. This represents how many people in the US for example were previously racist because societal influences but changed their ways after the civil rights movement. If predators are just black people, there is no good analogy for this. Black people were never in such a position of power over white people as Gray was to Judy in the childhood flashback sequence
4. The movie is about racial fear being weaponized for political gain rather than a simple "Racism is bad" message. The evil plot involves a sheep (an "oppressed" member of the population who advocates for little guys sticking together) being a secret mastermind trying to instill in the population this line of thought for power. Sounds a lot more like criticism of weaponizing racial divides from the modern American Left, making people blame racial divisions for problems (going from mild stereotyping to systemic career barriers) even in a society that has in truth (mild stereotyping still results from people trying to be nice or just protective, and the career barriers have more to do with Judy's size and not her prey status) moved past it, than saying "racism is bad" in general
5. Nick starts out a cynic. The most cynical people in the US are arguably "hillbillies" who are poor white people who by and large lost their ability to do honest work as society has really moved on from caring about their wellbeing since if you are white, you are privileged, right? But despite seeming strong and loud, they can oftentimes be victims as well, which is what Judy ends up realizing. I think she is supposed to start as an anti racist in the sense of viewing herself as a minority group and racism as solely being against people like her but then realized the more balanced worldview that prejudice can go from either direction. Again this angle wouldn't work as well if predators represented black people.

text:
The best thing about this movie is that it's NOT a weird metaphor for race or s*xuality in the same way many obvious kids' franchises are. There is no clear "this group is X" or even "this group is a minority". Roughly half of the animals are predators and half are prey, and throughout the movie, one group is facing prejudice from the other about the equal amount of time. Judy herself starts off being underappreciated and discriminated against (although there is also some very good reasoning for the huge predators to consider her not up to the standard in the physical sense), yet she constantly has to fight her own prejudices against the other group, and enda up being a part of, and then bringing down, a system to discriminate toward others. So ultimately, this is NOT a poorly disguised hamfisted metaphor of a political issue; this is a story that explores the general theme of prejudices, categorising people, stereotyping, identity, free will, and human connection.
If anything, I'd say the metaphor would be for men and women, since we're talking about two halves of "humanity" - and it does make great points viewed that way - but it makes those points in general, without applying such a narrow lens. It purposefully mixes up lots of clich√©s and familiar problems, because it's NOT interested in pushing a specific agenda - it wants to tell a story about human nature. It's not directed at some majority to Learn Their Lesson and Do Better, it's also not residing in the easy Stand Up To Bullies narrative. EVERYONE needs to stop fearing, blaming, and dehumanising others - and the only people who really benefit from pitting groups against eachother is the people who leverage the hate for their own benefit and power.

text:
What I find most clever about this movie is that Nick and Judy not only have great chemistry, but they're reflections of each other. Both of them faced bullying and mockery for their dreams because of prejudices over what they are (in Nick's case why would a boyscout camp even have muzzles like that where the kids could find them easily?) but only Nick gave up on that dream and became what he was seen as. What that was wasn't a scary dangerous predator, but a slick and deceptive scam artist with an eye for opportunity. And while he had his biases, he also knew how to read people as people.

Judy kept her optimism and determination but also the bias she grew up with, especially about foxes, which first shows when she calls Nick "a real articulate fella". The fact that she'd unwittingly imply that he's somehow well-spoken for a fox right after voicing her distain for the prejudice against them, and that they were teaching kids that exclusively predators used to just be violently aggressive monsters, makes it unsurprising that she latched onto that one possible explanation when confronted by the press without considering the the consequences.

It's a great example of two characters having a very similar experience but taking two very different paths as a result.

text:
16:22 yeah this is true. I think as you point out as a metaphor it still works. But I also think a few other things are worth pointing out.

mainly that predation, for most predators, is incredibly dangerous. Prey are risky to kill without getting mortally wounded in a world where there isn‚Äôt law enforcement protecting them, or social stigma dissuading the action in the first place. As long as the animals are evolved, and value staying alive over whatever instincts would cause them to consider predation, this is a non-issue, and betrays that the actual fear isn‚Äôt the predatory instinct, its the notion that the predators aren‚Äôt evolved enough for society, Wich is much closer to a textbook racist defense. 

Another thing that I think the movie does very intentionally is have the animals ‚Äògo savage‚Äô. Because while it is absolutely understandable about a prey animal being more concerned over a predator‚Äôs ability to kill them (without weapons) than a prey animal, but the problem is not a series of murderers where the murderers were all of sound mind. The problem is not predators choosing to do bad things because they are predators, and predators are predisposed to making bad choices, because they are naturally more evil. It‚Äôs obvious that they are loosing their ‚Äòevolution‚Äô and it‚Äôs also obvious, at least to me, that a prey animal also could. In this case they were directly being poisoned, but we can acknowledge Yes, it‚Äôs entirely plausible that the reason lay in biology or customs. But not because they are lesser, but because they are different. 

I think this movie could have been a weaker narrative but a better metaphor if the problem turned out to be some kind of chemical (maybe preservative) that was added to a niche brand of imitation meat. It breaks down into a toxin inside the body if you have a certain type of enzyme- an enzyme that very very few prey species have and most predators do(or vice versa if you don‚Äôt have the enzyme). The chemical had been tested a while ago (maybe before the mamal inclusion initiative updated safety testing standards) and deemed safe(prey outnumber preds 10/1), but mostly used in prey foods. Only recently did this particular product add it, without additional testing. 
I think that kind of resolution is much too dense and maybe a bit too dark for what Disney wanted, but it‚Äôs a lot closer to things that happen in real life. Like how so many safety/health tests aren‚Äôt done considering women(heart attack symptoms, nearly all drugs, especially thalidomide, car crashes) how some people are simply lactose intolerant, or have celiac disease. Celiac especially can cause you to go pretty insane if you eat a lot of stuff you shouldn‚Äôt. Things like prions also make you crazy, but only by eating from another animal (brains) so we absolutely could have anchored the metaphor better or more clearly, but it definitely wouldn‚Äôt have made for as good an ending for the movie‚Äôs target audience.

text:
Regarding the whole using a fictional world as a metaphor for real world racism, it's tricky but I think it depends a lot on how it's handled. Harry Potter for instance really needs you to subscribe to the death of the author theory just for how much Rowling has ruined it over the years going "werewolves are a metaphor for aids" or "house elves are a metaphor for slavery" (and then when people didn't pat her on the back for that she went full nut job because she has got to be the pettiest author on the planet).

Zootopia never tries to do a 1:1 metaphor. It creates it's own unique world and then sets up where the prejudice and racism might come from and invites people to question their own prejudices without ever going "oh, predators are a metaphor for gays or POCs". And generally it operates under the rules this world would have. Judy for instance is at a physical dissadvantage compared to most animals. Sloths are indeed slow. Nick literally exploits how what is a snack for an elephant can feed hundreds of rodents.

text:
I think part of the power of the allegory comes from the fact that the instance in the fictional world typically has a more tangible reason to be concerned and yet it doesn't nullify the point. In the X-Men the mutants do have powers and those do have the capacity to be a great danger. And yet this doesn't erase the fact that these mutants are people and they should still be able to have basic freedoms presuming they don't break the laws (just like other people).

I'm the case of Zootopia I think it maps on better to the real life case despite the dissimilarities. For one, at least within the story they're isn't a real current disposition towards harming others that predators feel. What is described as "primative" is better understood as a behavior of a different species that they are related to. So much like we wouldn't think of dogs worse because an ancient relative of them is hunted humans it is equally ridiculous to be scared of these humanoid versions of these creatures because an ancient ancestor of theirs was a different species that hunted other animals. And anyway, the point isn't lost as one the misconception is exactly that. Secondly, even if they had some slight disposition this is something closer to that which can be mitigated through intervention rather than a reduction of rights.

Overall, I agree to an extent that they are disanalogous in very important ways. But I think those ways highlight just how ridiculous the real life version is since we can see the issue with excessive discrimination in the fictional cases.

text:
The movie doesn't. It just expects the audience to know what to expect on a first day on a new job and doesn't correct Judy's wrong assumptions. From that, we can blame the chief for not caring and not explaining himself with even one sentence, but we can also blame AND understand Judy for going defensive and trying to prove herself. She clearly was out of line chasing a thief (and not even one who stole high-value items) into a tiny-animal district, endangering countless lives. Again, not being assigned to a partner, and not even given an explanation for what she did wrong, but instead firing her on the spot is what we can blame the chief for.

Interpreting this as racism is just people's interpretation, and a stupid one at that. It's the chief of the most high-profile district of the city being burdened with an officer so fresh from the academy that she's still wet behind the ears for political reasons and not giving a sh*t. He probably suspected that her being the best of her class was also political meddling. I have to concur with the filmmakers that that is something an audience should get without it being spelt out, but I disagree with them on whether it's something we can expect an audience to get without it being spelt out

text:
16:00 You're right Alex, these aren't the best representations of racism because they're technically based on (in movie) truths rather than untruths told to deny equality and justify systemic racism. Though the predator allegory works a little better because so much of early systemic racism was trying to justify it with science. Black people were studied to figure out if they were naturally stupid, slow, simple, etc... (spoiler alert, they're not). It still affects science and racism today. 

And when DNA testing became a widepread in labs there was a whole wave of science that tried to determine if there were biological causes for violent crime or delinquency in people's DNA, which fits well here - as in looking for a biological explanation rather than a social or external reason for things that are happening and have a history of happening (crime in predominantly colored and poor neighborhoods and predators becoming savage) but are in fact caused by systematic racism or in this case caused by biological espionage (also not the best fit for representing actual racism). 

So zootopia does some things a little better but it does still miss the mark. I think the best thing it does is encourage people to be curious about why people might be upset or angry or do bad things and consider what's happening to that person rather than making assumptions that it's "just how they are", as well as question racialized stereotypes.

I hope that makes sense. I'm have a bachelor's in anthropology and I'm in graduate school for American Studies fyi.

Bellweathers rant is actually a good representation of how systemic racism uses fear and moral superiority to increase racial and class divides. Though in our case it's the system doing it, not one radical sheep. (Although people like bellweather are how we get radical systemized racism).

text:
I've had to happen to me.

I forgot the guy even existed, and I didn't even consider myself "bullied". Sure they tried. But I always gave as good as I got. Half the time it was my idea. 

I had a couple of friends that were seniors in a small town high school when I was a freshman. They were also the biggest bullies in school. At least once a week they would grab one leg each, and drag me down the hallway. At the end we would do a sharp curve, and I would try to knock down as many freshmen that were standing around as possible. While pretending to actually be a victim. 

The principal was always annoyed that the freshman were constantly standing around right outside of his office. So he let us get away with it. He thought it was funny. 

The '80s and 90s was wild. Particularly if you lived in the boondocks, the backwoods, or nowhere in particular.

Anyway, I was super proud of the guy. I 100% thought he would be a loser and ruin his life. One of those moments that made me feel better, because my first reaction was to be happy for him. I can't be all that bad then. 

I finally remembered who he was and why I didn't remember him. I had gotten my revenge, he had to go to summer school because I fixed his grades. Somebody had accidentally changed his grades so he could play football. I just put them back to where they were supposed to be. I could do this because the school was too cheap to pay somebody to install the internet, or any of the computers. So I volunteered. And then just kind of kept running things. I even made all my back doors self-destruct on my way out. As long as they didn't mess with it, I left them with a perfectly running computer infrastructure when they started with nothing. 

So I've forgotten this guy because I had gotten my revenge, so he no longer existed to me, problem solved. 

So I could honestly tell him, "I had forgotten all about that, it's great to see you! I'm happy you're doing good." Etc.

It was weird. Good times!

text:
Zootopia isn't meant to be an allegory for modern American (or any country's) racial dynamics. It's meant to teach how prejudice in GENERAL works. The dynamics between predator and prey are meant to be logical for the world that's been crafted, not a 1:1 reflection of our own. If you'll notice, even animals within the same larger group (predator or prey) still have stereotypes about each other. For example, Chief Bogo and Judy. Bogo is a water buffalo, which is a large prey animal with few natural predators. He treats Judy, a fellow prey animal, poorly because she is a small animal with many natural predators. The same is true of other predatory animals treating Nick poorly because of the stereotype of foxes being sly and untrustworthy. 

In real life, people of the same larger group are still prejudiced against other subgroups. White people in Britain, America and Canada all have stereotypes of each other. European countries? Hated each other. African tribes? Hated each other. Native American tribes, Asian countries, all hated each other, even if they all belonged to the same supposed umbrella group of race. Every imaginable group historically hates every other group and human history is a never ending laundry list of bad blood. 

Racism is not and has never been a literal black and white matter, which is why the method this movie uses to tackle the concept is much smarter than a lot of people give it credit for.

text:
With every year I've come to hate this movie more. 

It seems like all anyone ever remembers this movie for is world building, it's twist villain, and the prejudice metaphor. 

The twist villain element is so short you might as well have just let the villain get a way and never revealed it.

The world building while detailed gets way too much praise and I feel overshadows all other aspects of this film. Creating a world that justifies having creatures of all shapes and sizes is nice, but it shouldn't be more valuable then the story. 

Let's be honest the whole predator and prey metaphor for racicim is bad a idea to be compared to rasicim because racism at its core has more to do with surface level traits.

text:
I love this movie SO much!

Judy is an adorkable character with an actual arc. She is tenacious and she's optimistic to a fault. She needs to learn humility and to let go of her (unconscious) biases.

* No, being the valedictorian doesn't immediately give her a pass to be let in on a complicated case. I'm with Bogo on this one, even if it worked out.
* She makes a HUGE mistake and hurts Nick big time. But she is strong enough to realise it and truly apologise. She doesn't sweep it under the rug.
* She learns to accept that not everything is rosy, and that she has to accept it.

Oh, and it's a WONDERFUL platonic relationship with these two without it being shoved down our throats. I think Zootopia and Wreck-It Ralph are the best movies in that degree.

I'm not sure I'm looking forward to the sequel ...

So fun fact, Zootopia wasn‚Äôt the original name for the movie. Before I saw the movie I came across a few posters in a mall advertising the movie as ‚ÄúZootropolis.‚Äù However I saw it under Zootopia when I did eventually see it in theaters. Same applies to a few more movie posters.



Edit: One more thing that will probably be classified as overthinking, but if there are Zooptopia versions of movies like Tangled and Wreck it Ralph and even a movie that got cancelled and is most likely never going to come out, does that mean there's a Zootopia version of Zootopia? Does this mean that there are animal versions of every franchise in this universe? Is that one Marvel Universe where Spider-Ham comes from canonically a children's comic who also has multiple different shows and movies? Is that DC world where Superman's a bunny also a comic in that universe with multiple movies and shows? If there are versions of Disney movies where everyone's some sort of animal in that universe, what does that say about other movies like the Robin Hood thirst trap movie or the entirety of Kung Fu Panda if it exists? Good luck debating all of this in your head.

text:
I think it is much better from the filmmakers deciding NOT to go dark and edgy with it. People are good at spotting OBVIOUS evil and prejudice. They're not as good at spotting the smaller, weaker injustices that add up to keep people down. The attitudes, the laziness, the assumptions, the quiet fear that divides people. The things one might say, meaning to be nice, that are still hurtful and ignorant. Instead of getting a fictional world that we can scoff at and easily say we're better than, we got something that cut closer to reality and said things about the world as it is.

We have a lot of ugly fictional dystopian worlds that talk about nightmarish oppression. Zootopia created a world a lot more like our own, and asked us to keep learning from each other and moving forward together.
